### Butter-Powder Tilt

The "Butter-Powder Tilt" is a rather quaint, if not entirely transparent, [price adjustment](/Quantity_adjustment) strategy that has found its footing within the agricultural policies of the [United States](/United_States). At its core, this mechanism mandates that the [United States Department of Agriculture (USDA)](/USDA) actively intervenes to uphold the farm price of milk, setting a benchmark at [$9.90 per hundredweight (cwt)](/United_States_dollar) for this essential commodity. The USDA's commitment extends to being perpetually ready to acquire any surplus butter, cheese, and nonfat [dry milk](/Powdered_milk) that may emerge when the prevailing wholesale prices for these dairy derivatives dip below certain administratively determined thresholds.

The legislative framework for this intricate dance of supply and demand was largely solidified by the [2002 farm bill](/2002_farm_bill), specifically under Section 1501 (Public Law 107–171). This pivotal piece of legislation granted the USDA the authority to recalibrate the government's purchasing prices for butter and nonfat dry milk on a bi-annual basis. The explicit objective behind these periodic adjustments was to achieve a more adept management of the government's stockpiles of surplus milk products, thereby aiming to mitigate the financial outlays associated with such holdings.

However, the operational nuance of the Butter-Powder Tilt lies in its inherent balancing act. Whenever the USDA decides to lower the purchase price for one of the designated commodities – be it butter or nonfat dry milk – it is simultaneously compelled to elevate the purchase price of the *other* commodity. This reciprocal adjustment is meticulously designed to ensure that the overarching support price for milk, pegged at the aforementioned $9.90 per cwt, remains unswayed. It is this peculiar, seesaw-like manipulation of prices between butter and nonfat dry milk that has given rise to the moniker "butter-powder tilt." It suggests a deliberate, if somewhat artificial, leaning in favor of one component over the other at any given moment, all in service of maintaining a stable overall milk price.

The strategy, while perhaps appearing straightforward in its stated goals, can lead to rather convoluted market dynamics. The USDA, in its role as a price stabilizer, effectively becomes a significant player in the dairy market, acting as a buyer of last resort. This interventionist approach is not without its critics, who often point to the potential for market distortions and the economic implications of government stockpiling. Nevertheless, the Butter-Powder Tilt persists as a key element in the [federal government's](/Federal_government_of_the_United_States) approach to supporting dairy farmers and ensuring a degree of price stability in a sector known for its volatility.

